// MovieThoughts.cshtml

@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Movie Thoughts";
}

<style>
    .full-bleed {
        margin-left: calc(-50vw + 50%);
        margin-right: calc(-50vw + 50%);
    }
</style>

<!-- PAGE HEADER -->
<div class="full-bleed" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1a1a00 0%, #0f0f00 60%, #0f0f0f 100%);">
    <div class="container py-5 text-center">
        <p class="text-warning text-uppercase fw-semibold small mb-2">Our Takes</p>
        <h1 class="display-4 fw-bold text-white mb-3">Movie Thoughts</h1>
        <p class="text-white-50 mx-auto" style="max-width:560px;">
            No spoiler warnings, no star systems — just raw, honest reflections on films that moved us,
            challenged us, or refused to leave our heads.
        </p>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- FEATURED THOUGHT -->
<div class="py-5">
    <p class="text-warning text-uppercase fw-semibold small mb-3">Featured</p>
    <div class="card bg-dark border-warning rounded-4 p-4 p-lg-5 text-white mb-2">
        <div class="row g-4 align-items-center">
            <div class="col-lg-8">
                <div class="d-flex gap-2 mb-3">
                    <span class="badge bg-warning text-dark">Drama</span>
                    <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary">2023</span>
                    <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary">By Kira</span>
                </div>
                <h2 class="fw-bold text-white mb-3">Past Lives Changed How I Think About Regret</h2>
                <p class="text-white-50 lh-lg mb-3">
                    I didn't cry during <em>Past Lives</em>. I cried three days later, standing in a queue,
                    thinking about a decision I made years ago. That's the kind of film this is —
                    it doesn't hit you in the cinema, it follows you home and waits.
                    Celine Song's debut is so precise in its emotional architecture that every scene
                    feels inevitable and heartbreaking at once.
                </p>
                <p class="text-white-50 lh-lg">
                    What lingers most is the film's argument that the life you didn't live
                    is always present in the one you did. In-yun, the Korean concept of fate
                    that threads the film together, becomes both comforting and devastating
                    depending on which character's eyes you're seeing through.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-4 text-center">
                <div class="bg-secondary rounded-3 d-flex align-items-center justify-content-center mb-3"
                     style="height:200px;font-size:4rem;">
                    🎭
                </div>
                <div class="text-warning fw-bold fs-4">★★★★★</div>
                <div class="text-secondary small">Past Lives · 2023</div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ALL THOUGHTS -->
<div class="full-bleed bg-black py-5">
    <div class="container py-2">
        <p class="text-warning text-uppercase fw-semibold small mb-1">All Entries</p>
        <h2 class="display-5 fw-bold text-white mb-4">Our Thought Log</h2>

        <div class="row g-4">

            <!-- Thought 1 -->
            <div class="col-lg-6">
                <div class="card bg-dark border-secondary h-100 p-4 text-white">
                    <div class="d-flex gap-2 mb-3 flex-wrap">
                        <span class="badge bg-warning text-dark">Sci-Fi</span>
                        <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary">2024</span>
                        <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary">By Adrian</span>
                    </div>
                    <h5 class="fw-bold mb-2">Dune: Part Two is a Sensory Event, Not Just a Film</h5>
                    <p class="text-white-50 small lh-lg mb-3">
                        Villeneuve didn't adapt Dune — he inhabited it. Part Two is the rare sequel that
                        makes the first film feel like a prologue. The sandworm scene alone is worth the
                        price of any cinema ticket. What strikes me most is how it trusts silence.
                        In a franchise landscape full of noise, Dune lets its images breathe.
                    </p>
                    <div class="d-flex align-items-center justify-content-between mt-auto">
                        <div class="text-warning">★★★★★</div>
                        <span class="text-secondary small">Dune: Part Two · 2024</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Thought 2 -->
            <div class="col-lg-6">
                <div class="card bg-dark border-secondary h-100 p-4 text-white">
                    <div class="d-flex gap-2 mb-3 flex-wrap">
                        <span class="badge bg-warning text-dark">History</span>
                        <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary">2023</span>
                        <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary">By Adrian</span>
                    </div>
                    <h5 class="fw-bold mb-2">Oppenheimer: When Spectacle Serves the Story</h5>
                    <p class="text-white-50 small lh-lg mb-3">
                        Three hours. No bathroom break. No regrets. Nolan's Oppenheimer is the film
                        that proved blockbuster cinema and genuine moral complexity don't have to be
                        mutually exclusive. Cillian Murphy carries the weight of history on his face
                        without saying a word. The Trinity sequence remains the most terrifying
                        three minutes of cinema I've seen this decade.
                    </p>
                    <div class="d-flex align-items-center justify-content-between mt-auto">
                        <div class="text-warning">★★★★★</div>
                        <span class="text-secondary small">Oppenheimer · 2023</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Thought 3 -->
            <div class="col-lg-6">
                <div class="card bg-dark border-secondary h-100 p-4 text-white">
                    <div class="d-flex gap-2 mb-3 flex-wrap">
                        <span class="badge bg-warning text-dark">Fantasy</span>
                        <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary">2023</span>
                        <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary">By Kira</span>
                    </div>
                    <h5 class="fw-bold mb-2">Poor Things is Gloriously, Defiantly Itself</h5>
                    <p class="text-white-50 small lh-lg mb-3">
                        Yorgos Lanthimos gave us a film that refuses to be anything other than
                        exactly what it is. Emma Stone's performance is a masterclass in playing
                        someone discovering the world for the first time with zero pre-existing
                        shame or social filters. It's funny, filthy, beautiful, and somehow
                        one of the most feminist films I've seen in years.
                    </p>
                    <div class="d-flex align-items-center justify-content-between mt-auto">
                        <div class="text-warning">★★★★★</div>
                        <span class="text-secondary small">Poor Things · 2023</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Thought 4 -->
            <div class="col-lg-6">
                <div class="card bg-dark border-secondary h-100 p-4 text-white">
                    <div class="d-flex gap-2 mb-3 flex-wrap">
                        <span class="badge bg-warning text-dark">Horror</span>
                        <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary">2024</span>
                        <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary">By Kira</span>
                    </div>
                    <h5 class="fw-bold mb-2">The Substance is Not for the Faint-Hearted (Go Anyway)</h5>
                    <p class="text-white-50 small lh-lg mb-3">
                        Coralie Fargeat took every anxiety women have about ageing, beauty standards,
                        and visibility — and turned them into something genuinely grotesque and brilliant.
                        It's excessive by design. The excess IS the point. I left the cinema feeling
                        disturbed, exhilarated, and oddly seen. Not an easy watch. An essential one.
                    </p>
                    <div class="d-flex align-items-center justify-content-between mt-auto">
                        <div class="text-warning">★★★★</div>
                        <span class="text-secondary small">The Substance · 2024</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Thought 5 — Zone of Interest -->
            <div class="col-lg-6">
                <div class="card bg-dark border-secondary h-100 p-4 text-white">
                    <div class="d-flex gap-2 mb-3 flex-wrap">
                        <span class="badge bg-warning text-dark">Drama</span>
                        <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary">2023</span>
                        <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary">By Adrian</span>
                    </div>
                    <h5 class="fw-bold mb-2">The Zone of Interest: Horror Through Absence</h5>
                    <p class="text-white-50 small lh-lg mb-3">
                        Jonathan Glazer's film shows you almost nothing and makes you feel everything.
                        A family living next to Auschwitz, going about their pleasant suburban life —
                        the horror is entirely off-screen, heard but never shown. It may be the most
                        disturbing film I've ever sat through, and one of the most important.
                    </p>
                    <div class="d-flex align-items-center justify-content-between mt-auto">
                        <div class="text-warning">★★★★★</div>
                        <span class="text-secondary small">The Zone of Interest · 2023</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Thought 6 — Disagreement card -->
            <div class="col-lg-6">
                <div class="card bg-dark border-warning h-100 p-4 text-white">
                    <div class="d-flex gap-2 mb-3 flex-wrap">
                        <span class="badge bg-warning text-dark">We Disagree</span>
                        <span class="badge bg-dark border border-secondary text-secondary">2024</span>
                    </div>
                    <h5 class="fw-bold mb-2">When We Don't Agree — And That's the Point</h5>
                    <p class="text-white-50 small lh-lg mb-3">
                        <strong class="text-white">Adrian:</strong> <em>Saltburn</em> is a gorgeous surface with nothing underneath. A vibe in search of a film.<br><br>
                        <strong class="text-white">Kira:</strong> Saltburn IS the surface — that's the entire thesis. It's a film about the seductive emptiness of wealth. Barry Keoghan understood the assignment perfectly.<br><br>
                        We've had this argument four times. We'll have it again.
                    </p>
                    <div class="d-flex align-items-center justify-content-between mt-auto">
                        <div>
                            <span class="text-warning small">Adrian: ★★★</span>
                            <span class="text-secondary small mx-2">·</span>
                            <span class="text-warning small">Kira: ★★★★½</span>
                        </div>
                        <span class="text-secondary small">Saltburn · 2023</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- FILTER HINT -->
<div class="py-5 text-center">
    <p class="text-white-50 mb-4">Want to explore by genre or see only our top-rated picks?</p>
    <div class="d-flex gap-3 justify-content-center flex-wrap">
        <a asp-controller="Movie" asp-action="TopPicks" class="btn btn-warning fw-semibold text-dark">View Top Picks</a>
        <a asp-controller="Movie" asp-action="Watchlist" class="btn btn-outline-warning">See Watchlist</a>
    </div>
</div>
